# 02 - Architecture

## Purpose

This document describes the high-level architecture of Nyx-Anvil.

It explains how the major components interact and defines the responsibilities of each architectural layer.

Implementation details are intentionally excluded from this document.

---

# Architectural Overview

Nyx follows an **Engine-First Architecture**.

The protection engine is the core of the system.

Every external integration communicates with the engine through stable public interfaces.

```text
                Adapters
                     │
                     ▼
                  CLI/API
                     │
                     ▼
            Protection Engine
                     │
      ┌──────────────┼──────────────┐
      ▼              ▼              ▼
 Obfuscation    Encryption    Integrity
                     │
                     ▼
                Algorithms
```

---

# Core Layers

Nyx is organized into five logical layers.

## Layer 1 — Algorithms

Algorithms implement individual protection techniques.

Examples include:

* Symbol renaming
* String encryption
* Integrity verification
* Anti-debugging techniques
* Future protection algorithms

Algorithms should remain independent whenever possible.

---

## Layer 2 — Protection Capabilities

Capabilities expose protection features to the engine.

Examples:

* Obfuscation
* Encryption
* Integrity
* Anti-Tamper
* Secret Protection

A capability may coordinate multiple algorithms to achieve a protection objective.

---

## Layer 3 — Protection Engine

The engine orchestrates the protection process.

Responsibilities include:

* Loading configuration
* Validating requests
* Building protection pipelines
* Executing capabilities
* Producing results

The engine is the single source of truth for all protection behavior.

---

## Layer 4 — Public Interfaces

Nyx exposes its functionality through stable public interfaces.

Examples include:

* Command Line Interface (CLI)
* Native API
* Future integrations

These interfaces should remain lightweight and should never implement protection logic.

---

## Layer 5 — Adapters

Adapters integrate Nyx into external development environments.

Examples include:

* Visual Studio Code
* JetBrains IDEs
* Godot Editor
* Unreal Editor
* Visual Studio
* CI/CD systems

Adapters improve developer experience without changing engine behavior.

---

# Architectural Rules

The following dependency rules apply.

```
Adapters
    ↓

CLI / API
    ↓

Engine
    ↓

Capabilities
    ↓

Algorithms
```

Dependencies must only flow downward.

Lower layers must never depend on higher layers.

---

# Separation of Responsibilities

Each layer owns a single responsibility.

| Layer        | Responsibility                     |
| ------------ | ---------------------------------- |
| Algorithms   | Implement protection techniques    |
| Capabilities | Organize protection features       |
| Engine       | Coordinate protection execution    |
| CLI/API      | Expose stable public interfaces    |
| Adapters     | Integrate with developer workflows |

Responsibilities should not overlap.

---

# Engine-Centered Design

The engine defines the behavior of Nyx.

Editors, IDEs, and integrations must behave as clients of the engine.

No adapter should produce protection behavior that differs from another adapter when given the same inputs.

---

# Architectural Goals

The architecture is designed to achieve the following goals.

* Modularity
* Extensibility
* Deterministic behavior
* Cross-platform support
* Editor independence
* Consistent developer experience
* Long-term maintainability

---

# Summary

Nyx separates protection logic from developer integrations.

The engine remains the core of the system, while adapters focus exclusively on integrating Nyx into different development environments.

This architecture allows Nyx to evolve independently of any specific editor, IDE, framework, or game engine.
